{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The MDP framework ensures that the robot can adapt its actions based on real-time environmental changes and task requirements.1) MDP Formalization: The MDP is defined as a tuple M = (S, A, T, R, γ), where:• S represents the state space, which includes:-Robot joint configurations q ∈ R n, -Object poses p o ∈ SE(3), -Environmental parameters e ∈ R m, -Task progress indicators τ ∈ [0, 1].• A defines the action space, consisting of:-Primitive actions a p ∈ A p (e.g., grasp, push, lift), -Composite actions a c ∈ A c derived from action sequences, -Control parameters θ ∈ Θ for action execution.• T: S ×A×S → [0, 1] represents the transition function:-T (s ′ |s, a) = P (s t+1 = s ′ |s t = s, a t = a), -Incorporates environmental dynamics and action uncertainties, -Updated through the EKG based on execution outcomes.• R: S × A × S → R defines the reward function:R(s, a, s ′) = w 1 r i + w 2 r p + w 3 r s, where:r i (s, a, s ′) represents immediate rewards for action completion, r p (τ) denotes progress rewards for task advancement, r s (s) indicates safety penalties for approaching constraints.• γ ∈ [0, 1) is the discount factor balancing immediate and future rewards.",
    "2) Task Decomposition and Action Selection: Tasks are decomposed into subtasks using a hierarchical structure:1) High-level task representation:T = {(g 1, ϕ 1),..., (g n, ϕ n)},where g i represents subtask goals and ϕ i defines constraints.",
    "2) Task plan selection policy π: S → A:• Derived through value iteration:V * (s) = max a∈A R(s, a) + γ s ′ ∈S T (s ′ |s, a)V * (s ′),• Policy extraction:π * (s) = arg max a∈A R(s, a) + γ s ′ ∈S T (s ′ |s, a)V * (s ′).3) Action sequence validation through EKG:• Feasibility check: F(π, ϕ) → {0, 1}, • Safety verification: V(π, s) → {0, 1}.3) Feedback Loop and Learning: The feedback loop integrates execution outcomes to refine both the MDP components and the EKG:1) State-Action-Reward Collection:• Execution traces: ξ = {(s t, a t, r t, s t+1)} T t=0, • Performance metrics: M(ξ) = {success, efficiency, safety}.2) Model Update Rules:• Transition function update:T ′ (s ′ |s, a) = (1 -α)T (s ′ |s, a) + αI (s,a,s ′) (ξ),• Reward function refinement: R ′ (s, a, s ′) = R(s, a, s ′) + β∆(M(ξ)),• EKG knowledge update: EKG ′ = EKG ⊕ {{ξ, M(ξ)}}.",
    "3) Policy Improvement:• Value function update using collected experiences,• Policy refinement through gradient-based optimization: θ ′ = θ + η∇ θ J(π θ).",
    "I. Real-Time Validation with GATsGraph Attention Networks (GATs) address the challenge of real-time validation by dynamically prioritizing safety-critical nodes in the Embodied Knowledge Graph (EKG), such as fragile objects (e.g., glassware), dynamic obstacles (e.g., moving humans), or temperature-sensitive items (e.g., hot beverages)."
  ],
